    "imageSrc": "/alicia-lollar.jpg",
    "bio1": "Alicia Lollar, is a Senior Engineer II in the Technical Research and Development department at BNSF. Alicia started what was to be a four-month contractor position as a project/material manager which turned into a 27-year (and counting) career in the RT&D at BNSF. She still manages projects, but her duties expanded over the years to include weld quality control, fuel testing, gage-face lubricator testing and site inspections. Currently, her main focus is on derailment investigations and failure analysis. She has investigated or been involved in more than 650 derailment investigations. Most of them have involved broken components, such as wheels, axles, side frames, knuckles, rail, welds, joint bars, etc. Alicia works closely with the mechanical and engineering detector groups to help them improve their detectors. She is on the MD-115 Tag team, which reviews the industry wheel failures every month, and the FRA Wheel Failure R&D program, which started in 2016. She organizes and teaches Derailment Analysis and Prevention workshops across the BNSF system.",
    "bio2": "She holds a B.S. in Anthropology and a B.S. in Life Science, from Kansas State University.",
    "abstract1": "The most common failure modes in freight railroad wheels in North America are shattered rims, vertical split rims, and plate failures. Although less common, occasionally wheels fail due to fatigue cracks initiating at the back rim surface. These failure modes have been the root cause of derailments. BNSF Railway along with other Class I Railroads in North America reported wheel failures involving fatigue cracks initiating at the back rim surface. BNSF has noticed an increase in the frequency of derailments caused by this failure mode with six derailments occurring between the years 2019 and 2023. These failures have occurred in both forged and cast wheels from different wheel manufacturers. This failure mode is not new. Previous work by Opinsky [1] presented his findings on this type of failure which were mainly related to visual inspection, data, and fracture mechanics. There were no metallographic findings reported. In this study, using metallographic methods, the authors showed that the cause of the failure was thermally induced fatigue cracking which initiated in the back rim surface where there was a band of scraping marks. Metallographic testing conducted on the failed and mate wheels of six different wheelsets received from BNSF derailments which occurred from 2019 to 2023 revealed similar results.",
